This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

Consider the following scenario. There is an assembly with the following code: 

```csharp
public class C 
{
    public int Prop { get;  set; }
}
```

Now using the `INamedTypeSymbol` for `C` in a consuming compilation where we have `MetadataImportOptions.Public` the following will happen:

```csharp
INamedTypeSymbol symbol = GetSymbolForC(); 
// This includes Prop and backing field of prop
_ = symbol.MemberNames;  

// This returns only Prop
symbol.GetMembers();

// This includes only Prop 
_ = symbol.MemberNames;  
```

The reason for this is that `MemberNames` does not consider `MetadataImportOptions` but `GetMembers` does. Further the end of `GetMembers` will [replace the underlying](https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/blob/main/src/Compilers/CSharp/Portable/Symbols/Metadata/PE/PENamedTypeSymbol.cs#L1473-L1477) data store of `MemberNames` with the result of `GetMembers`. Because on considers `MetadataImportOptions` and the other does not it leads to a disconnect about the final state of `MemberNames`. 

There are a couple of ways we could approach this.

**Option 1**
 The simplest is to just guard the final part of `GetMembers` to avoid overwriting the result of `MemberNames`. That is a very easy fix: 

```csharp
// Check just to avoid an unnecessary allocation in common case MemberNames is 
// called before this
if (_lazyMemberNames is null)
{
  var memberNames = SpecializedCollections.ReadOnlyCollection(membersDict.Keys);
  _ = Interlocked.CompareExchange(ref _lazyMemberNames, memberNames, null);
}
```

That has the downside though that the behavior of the API depends on the order in which they are called. That is true already though so it's not a regression in that sense. 

**Option 2**
Fix `MemberNames` to respect `MetadataImportOptions`. This is the preferred fix as it gives the consistency between what the two APIs return. It does add a bit of cost as we need to do a minimal amount of metadata importing to filter out the values. That is roughly just reading an `enum` and doing a quick test on it so likely acceptable in the context of `MemberNames`. 

Believe we should consider option 2 first and fall back to 1 if the performance is unacceptable. 

**Option 3**
Chaneg `GetMemberNames` such that it builds up `MemberNames` irrespective of accessibility.

**Version Used**:  .NET 7

(Before you think this is a crazy scenario, the use case is generated code.)

**Steps to Reproduce**:
(Unfortunately, this can't be demonstrated in a gist, because it requires multiple files.)
1. In one file:
```
file interface IFoo
{
    IReadOnlyDictionary<int, string> Bar { get; }
}

internal partial class Foo : IFoo
{
    private readonly Dictionary<int, string> _bar = new() { { 1, "one" }, { 2, "two" } };
    IReadOnlyDictionary<int, string> IFoo.Bar => _bar;
}
```
2. In a second file:
```
file interface IFoo
{
    IReadOnlyDictionary<int, string> Bar { get; }
}

internal partial class Foo : IFoo
{
    IReadOnlyDictionary<int, string> IFoo.Bar => _bar;
}
```
3. After getting no complaints in Visual Studio, compile.

**Diagnostic Id**: CS0102

4. Change second file:
```
file interface IFoo
{
    IReadOnlyDictionary<int, string> Bar { get; }
}

internal partial class Foo : IFoo
{
}
```
(`Foo` needs to implement `IFoo` because, elsewhere in the file, an instance of `Foo` will be passed to a method taking `IFoo`.)

5. Visual Studio complains that `Foo` doesn't implement `IFoo`.

6.  Compile.

**Diagnostic Id**: CS0535

**Expected Behavior**: The compiler recognizes that `IFoo.Bar` in the part of `Foo` in one file is different from `IFoo.Bar` in a different part because each `IFoo` is file scoped and is therefore a different type. Seeing these as different types, the compiler does not emit CS0102 and compiles the code.

**Actual Behavior**: The compiler confuses file scoped types with the same name and emits CS0102 and doesn't compile the code.
